         <entryFree xml:id="k000146" type="architectural feature">
            <term xml:id="term-k000146-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt">xuanshan</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000146-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">懸山</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000146-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">悬山</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000146-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">xúanshān</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000146-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">hsüan-shan</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000146-6" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000146-1">overhanging gable roof</term>
            
            <note type="Note">
               <p xml:lan="en" source="#biblk000146-2">A term commonly used in the <term ref="/keyword/k000070">Qing</term> dynasty for a two-sloped, gable roof which extends beyond the wall plane on the gable ends (Guo 2002, 86). This type can also be called a <term>xuanshanding 懸山頂</term>, where ding 頂 means roof (Fu 2017, 370).</p>
               <p xml:lan="en" source="#biblk000146-3">Meaning, literally, “overhanging-peak,” xuanshan is a term describing a traditional Chinese gable roof, in which the eaves of the gable, 
                  supported by purlins, extend past the wall on the gable ends. The earliest extant wooden building with a xuanshan roof is the West Side Hall <placeName ref="/place/000207">(Xi peidian 西配殿) of Longmensii 龍門寺</placeName> 
                  in Pingshun County 平順 (940 CE). However, the term xuanshan first surfaced in Qing dynasty literature (e.g. GCZF 7.4b, 8.7b). This term was likely invented to distinguish it from 
                  yingshan <term ref="/keyword/k000147">硬山</term>, a gable roof popular from the Ming dynasty, in which the eaves of the gable are flush with the wall surface.</p>
               <!--<p xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#biblk000146-2">一種兩坡，並且在山面挑出的屋頂形式。</p> -->
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">懸山是中國傳統建築的一種屋頂形式，指前後兩坡，檁木挑出於山墻或山面梁架之外，且兩坡屋面隨檁木懸出的屋頂形式。已知現存最早的此種木構建築屋頂形式實例為山西平順龍門寺西配殿（五代）。
                  但“懸山”一詞最早出現于清代文獻（如《工程做法》7.4b, 8.7b），很可能是由於從明代開始，山面並不出挑的兩坡屋面，即硬山，逐漸普遍，需要對兩種屋頂形式進行區分，故而產生“懸山”一詞，以指代山面出挑的兩坡屋頂形式。 </p>   
            </note>
